<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Lufilya Secondary School Management System Documentation</title>
  <style>
    body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #172033; line-height: 1.45; }
    h1 { color: #06224a; text-align: center; }
    h2 { color: #0b3a75; border-bottom: 1px solid #b7dcf4; padding-bottom: 4px; }
    h3 { color: #06224a; }
    table { border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; margin: 10px 0 18px; }
    th, td { border: 1px solid #b7dcf4; padding: 8px; text-align: left; }
    th { background: #e0f2fe; color: #06224a; }
    .note { background: #eef8ff; border: 1px solid #b7dcf4; padding: 10px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Lufilya Secondary School Management System</h1>
  <p><strong>Documentation:</strong> How the system works</p>
  <p><strong>School:</strong> Lufilya Secondary School</p>

  <h2>1. System Overview</h2>
  <p>
    The Lufilya Secondary School Management System is a web-based application built with React for the frontend
    and FastAPI for the backend. It helps the school manage teachers, students, fees, scores, academic reports,
    announcements, and system activity.
  </p>
  <p>
    The system uses one login page, but users are taken to different interfaces depending on their role.
    Each interface has its own sidebar and tools.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Default Login Credentials</h2>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Role</th><th>Email</th><th>Password</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Admin</td><td>lumbani@gmail.com</td><td>lum2004</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Bursar</td><td>bursar@lufilya.edu.mw</td><td>bursar123</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Headteacher</td><td>head@lufilya.edu.mw</td><td>head123</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Teacher</td><td>teacher@lufilya.edu.mw</td><td>teacher123</td></tr>
  </table>
  <p class="note">
    After login, every user can open the Credentials tab and change their password. The system requires
    users to confirm the new password before saving.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Main Interfaces</h2>

  <h3>3.1 Admin Interface</h3>
  <p>The Admin manages the school setup and staff records. The Admin can:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Register new teachers.</li>
    <li>Assign junior and senior subjects to teachers.</li>
    <li>Assign classes to teachers.</li>
    <li>Assign roles such as Headteacher and Bursar to registered teachers.</li>
    <li>View system activity logs.</li>
    <li>Manage teacher credentials created during registration.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3.2 Teacher Interface</h3>
  <p>The Teacher works with classes and subjects assigned by the Admin. The Teacher can:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Select a class, term, and registered subject before entering scores.</li>
    <li>Enter scores for students in the selected class.</li>
    <li>Upload scores using an Excel or CSV file where supported.</li>
    <li>View subject performance summaries.</li>
    <li>See performance groups such as most performing, moderate, and least performing students.</li>
    <li>Work only with subjects and classes assigned to that teacher.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3.3 Bursar Interface</h3>
  <p>The Bursar manages students and fees. The Bursar can:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Register students with full name, date of birth, village, form, sex, guardian phone, guardian email, and health status.</li>
    <li>Generate student registration numbers automatically, for example LIF2024001.</li>
    <li>View fees status for all registered students.</li>
    <li>See paid, not paid, and balance information.</li>
    <li>Update student payments.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3.4 Headteacher Interface</h3>
  <p>The Headteacher monitors school performance and produces reports. The Headteacher can:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>View registered students.</li>
    <li>View fee statements.</li>
    <li>View performance by class.</li>
    <li>Generate report cards by selecting class and term.</li>
    <li>Use scores entered by teachers to generate reports.</li>
    <li>Write announcements.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>4. Subjects</h2>
  <h3>4.1 Junior Secondary Subjects - JCE, Forms 1 and 2</h3>
  <p>
    English Language, Chichewa, Mathematics, Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Geography, History,
    Social &amp; Life Studies, Bible Knowledge, Agriculture, Computer Studies, Business Studies,
    Home Economics, Technical Studies.
  </p>

  <h3>4.2 Senior Secondary Subjects - MSCE, Forms 3 and 4</h3>
  <p>
    English, Chichewa, Mathematics, Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Geography, History,
    Social &amp; Life Studies, Bible Knowledge, Agriculture, Computer Studies, Business Studies,
    Home Economics, Technical Drawing.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Grading Rules</h2>
  <h3>5.1 JCE Grading - Forms 1 and 2</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Marks</th><th>Grade</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
    <tr><td>80 - 100</td><td>A</td><td>Excellent</td></tr>
    <tr><td>70 - 79</td><td>B</td><td>Very Good</td></tr>
    <tr><td>55 - 69</td><td>C</td><td>Good</td></tr>
    <tr><td>40 - 54</td><td>D</td><td>Average / Pass</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0 - 39</td><td>F</td><td>Fail</td></tr>
  </table>
  <p>
    A JCE student passes when they pass at least six subjects and English Language is included among the passed subjects.
  </p>

  <h3>5.2 MSCE Grading - Forms 3 and 4</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Marks</th><th>Grade</th><th>Category</th></tr>
    <tr><td>80 - 100</td><td>1</td><td>Distinction</td></tr>
    <tr><td>70 - 79</td><td>2</td><td>Distinction</td></tr>
    <tr><td>65 - 69</td><td>3</td><td>Credit</td></tr>
    <tr><td>60 - 64</td><td>4</td><td>Credit</td></tr>
    <tr><td>55 - 59</td><td>5</td><td>Credit</td></tr>
    <tr><td>50 - 54</td><td>6</td><td>Credit</td></tr>
    <tr><td>45 - 49</td><td>7</td><td>Pass</td></tr>
    <tr><td>40 - 44</td><td>8</td><td>Pass</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0 - 39</td><td>9</td><td>Fail</td></tr>
  </table>
  <p>
    For MSCE, the system calculates points using the best six subjects. The valid points range is 6 to 48.
    A student must also pass English.
  </p>

  <h2>6. Reports</h2>
  <p>
    Report cards are generated from scores entered by teachers. The Headteacher selects the class and term,
    then the system prepares learner performance reports showing subjects, scores, grades, ranks, remarks,
    position in class, school announcements, next term details, and account details.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Layout and Navigation</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Each interface has a left sidebar with tabs.</li>
    <li>The sidebar can be hidden or shown using the Hide menu / Show menu button.</li>
    <li>The header is fixed and does not move when scrolling.</li>
    <li>The working area scrolls independently under the fixed header.</li>
    <li>The system shows greetings based on time, such as Good morning, Good afternoon, or Good evening.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>8. Running the System Locally</h2>
  <p>To run the system locally, start the FastAPI server and open the browser at:</p>
  <p><strong>http://127.0.0.1:8000</strong></p>
  <p>Default command:</p>
  <p><code>python -m uvicorn backend.main:app --host 127.0.0.1 --port 8000</code></p>

  <h2>9. Important Notes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>The Admin should register teachers before assigning subjects, classes, or roles.</li>
    <li>Teachers can only see subjects and classes assigned to them.</li>
    <li>Bursar records student fees and updates payments.</li>
    <li>Headteacher generates reports using teacher-entered scores.</li>
    <li>Users should change default passwords after first login.</li>
  </ul>
</body>
</html>
